It also offers EZ-IO power driver, which is designed to penetrate the intraosseous space by drilling through the bone with a hollow needle and integrated stylet that doubles as the forward cutting bit to secure its correct placement; and EZ-IO Vascular Access Pack, a kit developed for emergency medical specialists to provide access to IV and IO devices to gain vascular access. Description: InfraScan is a medical device company.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Philadelphia Area, Great Lakes, Northeastern US
Full Description: InfraScan is a medical device company that invented and distributes hand-held diagnostic devices for head injury and stroke assessment based on Near-Infrared (NIR) technology. The Infrascanner enables clinicians to effectively, conveniently, and accurately detect intracranial bleeding in patients with head trauma. Intracranial hematomas are an important and, if diagnosed early, treatable cause of secondary brain injury in patients with head trauma. Recent statistics from Iraq shows that 30% of all wounded in action have head injuries, and 40% of them have brain hematomas. Dr. Britton Chance (University of Pennsylvania) and Dr. Claudia Robertson (Baylor College of Medicine) invented a NIR system for detection of brain hematomas and tested it successfully in 305 patients in Baylor. An entrepreneurial team formed a company around this technology in collaboration with Drexel University and won the Wharton Business Plan competition in April 2004 and the second prize at the global business plan competition in Singapore in October 2004. The Office of Naval Research funded the company in May, the Biotechnology Greenhouse of Southeastern Pennsylvania, from Ben Franklin Technology Partners of Southeastern Pennsylvania, and from Philadelphia Industrial Development Corporation. A multi-center clinical study to support an FDA submission started in July 2006, and on February 2008 an application was submitted to the FDA.
Industry Groups: Biotechnology, Health Care, Science and Engineering

Description: Fastrip carries the typical convenience store products (drinks, snacks, etc.).

Full Description: Fastrip distinguishes itself from other convenience stores by offering commitments to customers. They do not only offer the products that everyone expects at a convenience store (drinks, snacks, etc.) but also offer great prices on all the items needed between weekly grocery shopping trips - milk, bread, and eggs. When customers run out of any other grocery item (sugar, flour, salt, etc), they can find it stocked at Fastrip at a reasonable price. Rather than going to the supermarket and parking and walking for 15-20 minutes to get milk and eggs, their customers come to Fastrip and are out within two minutes. They are a convenient mini supermarket. The company saves their customers money and time. Founded in 1968, Fastrip began as a small dairy store in Bakersfield, CA. Initially, they sold only dairy products and limited grocery items. Their grocery selection expanded within a few years, as well as their gas options. After their first success, they expanded, bringing their concept of great selection, value, and customer service to Bakersfield as well. The company has expanded throughout California after growing in Bakersfield and Kern County.  As a company, they always sought markets that were underserved and where they could offer added value. Today, they operate 53 stores in California and Arizona, all of which offer 24-hour convenience.

Description: Ivivi Technologies, Inc., a medical technology company, engages in designing, developing, and commercializing electrotherapeutic
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: Ivivi Technologies, Inc., a medical technology company, engages in designing, developing, and commercializing electrotherapeutic technologies for the chronic wound, plastic and reconstructive surgery, and other therapeutic medical markets. Its pulsed electromagnetic field (tPEMF) technology utilizes a magnetic field to create a therapeutic electrical field in injured tissue; and provides electrochemical information, which modulates relevant biochemical pathways. The company’s tPEMF signals are used to enhance the specific physiological processes, including that generate the body's natural anti-inflammatory response and tissue repair. Its products include SofPulse M-10, Roma, and Torino PEMF products that utilize tPEMF technology to treat edema and pain in soft tissue. The company’s products consist of three components: tPEMF signal, signal generator, and applicators. The signal generator produces a specific tPEMF signal that is pulsed through the applicator. The applicator transmits the tPEMF signal into the soft tissue target, penetrating medical dressings, casts, coverings, clothing, and other non-metal materials. Its products are used for the treatment of acute or chronic wounds, including serious trauma wounds, failed surgical closures, amputations, pressure ulcers, and post surgical wounds; edema and pain following plastic and reconstructive surgery procedures; and pain associated with the inflammatory phase of chronic conditions. Ivivi Technologies, Inc. sells and rents its products to nursing facilities, rehabilitation hospitals, acute care hospitals and facilities, and home health care systems through third-party distributors, contract therapy service companies in the United States, Canada, and the European Union. Ivivi Technologies, Inc. was founded in 1989 and is headquartered in Montvale, New Jersey.
Industry Groups: Biotechnology, Health Care, Science and Engineering

Description: Morgan Stanley is a financial services and asset management corporation.
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: Dean Witter Reynolds was an American stock brokerage and securities firm catering to retail clients. Prior to its acquisition, it was among the largest retail firms in the securities industry with over 9,000 account executives (ranking third in the US in 1996) and was among the largest members of the New York Stock Exchange. The company served over 3.2 million clients primarily in the U.S. Dean Witter provided debt and equity underwriting and brokerage as well as mutual funds and other saving and investment products for individual investors. The company's asset management arm, Dean Witter InterCapital, with total assets of $90.0 billion prior to acquisition, was one of the largest asset management operations in the U.S. In 1997, Dean Witter's parent company Dean Witter, Discover, Inc., which also owned Discover Card, merged with investment banking house Morgan Stanley to form Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. The combined firm later dropped the Dean Witter name. In 2009, the Dean Witter retail operations were transferred to Morgan Stanley Smith Barney, a joint venture with Citigroup. For many years, the company used the corporate slogan, "We measure success one investor at a time," which was later adopted by Morgan Stanley.
